-- Hong Kong's Stocks Drop to Two-Month Low; HSBC Holdings, Developers Fall
-- B y   H a n n y   W a n   a n d   J o n a t h a n   B u r g o s
-- 2010-12-20T09:30:31Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-12-20/hong-kong-s-stocks-drop-to-two-month-low-hsbc-holdings-developers-fall.html
Hong Kong  stocks  fell, dragging the
benchmark index to its lowest level in more than two months, as
concern mounted Europe’s debt crisis will spread, and developers
slid after reports of lower property sales in the city.  HSBC Holdings Plc, Europe’s biggest bank, dropped 1.1
percent. New World Development Co., a developer controlled by
billionaire  Cheng Yu-tung , retreated 2.2 percent.  Li Ning Co. 
plunged 16 percent after the Chinese sportswear maker, set up by
a former Olympic gymnast of the same name, said orders declined.  The  Hang Seng Index  lost 0.3 percent to 22,639.08, its
lowest close since Oct. 4. Shares also declined on concern North
Korea will retaliate against South Korean artillery drills this
afternoon.  “Europe’s debt problems are continuing to affect risk
appetite,” said  Yoji Takeda , who helps manage about $1.1
billion at RBC Investment (Asia) Ltd. in Hong Kong. “There’s
also a slight concern on escalating tensions in the Korean
peninsula, though it’s unlikely to develop into a major
skirmish.”  The  Hang Seng China Enterprises Index  of so-called H shares
of Chinese companies slipped 0.5 percent to 12,408.49.  The Hang Seng Index has recovered 19 percent from this
year’s low on May 25 on speculation that growth in corporate
earnings will overcome concerns about the pace of the U.S.
economic recovery and China’s steps to curb rising property
prices. Shares in the gauge trade at an average 14.2 times
estimated earnings, compared with 12.7 times on May 25.  Central Bank  People’s Bank of China Governor  Zhou Xiaochuan  said the
central bank is weighing possible effects on the stock market
when deciding economic policy, though it “can hardly cover all
the bases” given “a limited number of policy tools,” China
Central Television reported on Dec. 18.  HSBC lost 1.1 percent to HK$79.25. Standard Chartered Plc,
a London-based bank, slid 1.7 percent to HK$210.  European stocks fell on Dec. 17 on concern that some euro-
area nations won’t be able to repay their debts. Ireland’s
credit rating was cut five levels by Moody’s Investors Service
on Dec. 17.  New World retreated 2.2 percent to HK$14.32. Hang Lung
Properties Ltd., Hong Kong’s third-largest developer by market
value, declined 1.5 percent to HK$35.75.  Hong Kong used-apartment sales fell 63 percent in the five
weekends since the government introduced measures to cool the
property market, the Ming Pao Daily reported today.  Property Sales  New mortgage applications and property sales are set to
drop by 20 percent next year because of the cooling measures,
the Standard reported, citing Hang Seng Bank Ltd. Executive
Director  William Leung Wing-cheung .  Li Ning slumped 16 percent to HK$17.88. Orders for the
second quarter of 2011 have fallen and operating costs are
rising, the company said, citing the results of its trade fair.
Order volumes of apparel declined more than 7 percent from a
year earlier, according to a statement.  China Shineway Pharmaceutical Group Ltd., a manufacturer of
Chinese medicine, dropped 3.8 percent to HK$22.70.  Sihuan
Pharmaceutical Holdings Group Ltd. , which sells treatments for
heart disease and stroke in China, lost 1.6 percent to HK$5.68.  China’s National Development and Reform Commission may cut
drug prices by an average 40 percent for 658 different items,
the Economic Observer reported, citing unidentified drug company
officials.  China Construction Bank Corp. , the nation’s No. 2 lender by
market value, fell 0.7 percent to HK$6.92 after Xinhua News
Agency said the bank’s new lending next year will be less than
in 2010.  More than five stocks fell for every three that gained
among the 45 constituents of the Hang Seng Index. Its futures
advanced 0.1 percent to 22,699.  To contact the reporter on this story:
 Hanny Wan  in Hong Kong at 
 hwan3@bloomberg.net .  To contact the editor responsible for this story:
